H1> Posting news

P> News is the spine of most e107 sites. Items can be grouped under categories, scheduled, hidden behind a "read more" cut, and restricted by user class.

SHOT> news/admin-newspost.png | News editor with Body and Extended fields

H1> Categories

Q> What are news categories for?
A> They group news items into themes (e.g. "Releases", "Community"). Each category can have its own icon, so visitors can identify and filter items at a glance.

H1> Body vs Extended

Q> What is the Extended box for?
A> It holds the long-form portion of an article. The [b]Body[/b] field stores a short intro shown in lists; the [b]Extended[/b] field is revealed when the visitor clicks [i]Read more[/i]. Use this combo whenever the full article is longer than a few paragraphs.

TIP> A short, attention-grabbing Body increases click-through to the full article. Treat it like an editorial lead.

H1> Scheduling and visibility

Q> What are the activation boxes for?
A> They schedule when a news item is visible. Set a [b]start[/b] date to publish in the future, an [b]end[/b] date to expire automatically, or leave both blank to publish immediately and indefinitely.

Q> I entered a news item and it says "News saved in database" – does that mean it will show on my news page?
A> It means the text was saved successfully. Whether visitors see it depends on the [b]active[/b] flag and the activation dates: if the item is active and within its visibility window, it appears on the news page.

NOTE> Drafts are useful: leave [b]active[/b] unticked while you iterate on the article, then flip it on when ready.
